Definition 1.16. We call a sequence of $S$-semimodules $L\overset{f}{\longrightarrow}M\overset{g}{\longrightarrow}N$ exact iff $f(L)=\mathrm{Ker}(g)$ and $g$ is $k$-uniform. An exact sequence $0\longrightarrow L\overset{f}{\longrightarrow}M\overset{g}{\longrightarrow}N\longrightarrow 0$ is called a short exact sequence.
Definition 3.3. Let $F$ be a right $S$-semimodule and $\mathcal{M}$ a class of left $S$-semimodules. We say that $F$ is uniformly flat w.r.t. $\mathcal{M}$ (or uniformly $\mathcal{M}$-flat) iff for every exact sequence of left $S$-semimodules $0\longrightarrow L\overset{f}{\longrightarrow}M\overset{g}{\longrightarrow}N% \longrightarrow 0,$ with $M\in\mathcal{M},$ the following sequence of Abelian monoids is exact $0\longrightarrow F\otimes_{S}L\overset{\mathrm{id}_{F}\otimes_{S}f}{% \longrightarrow}F\otimes_{S}M\overset{\mathrm{id}_{F}\otimes_{S}g}{% \longrightarrow}F\otimes_{S}N\longrightarrow 0.$ If $F_{S}$ is uniformly $M$-flat for every left $S$-semimodule ${}_{S}M,$ then we say that $F$ is uniformly flat.
Definition 1.5. Let $S$ be a semiring. A right $S$-semimodule is an algebraic structure $(M,+,0_{M})$ consisting of a non-empty set $M,$ a binary operation “$+$” along with a right $S$-action $M\times S\longrightarrow M,\text{ }(m,s)\mapsto ms,$ such that: 1. $(M,+,0_{M})$ is an Abelian monoid with neutral element $0_{M};$ 2. $(ms)s^{\prime}=m(ss^{\prime}),$ $(m+m^{\prime})s=ms+m^{\prime}s$ and $m(s+s^{\prime})=ms+ms^{\prime}$ for all $s,s^{\prime}\in S$ and $m,m^{\prime}\in M;$ 3. $m1_{S}=m$ and $m0_{S}=0_{M}=0_{M}s$ for all $m\in M$ and $s\in S.$
Definition 3.20. We say that the semiring $S$ is a left (uniformly) Baer’s semiring iff every (uniformly) injective left $S$-semimodule is (uniformly) injective. The right (uniformly) Baer-injective semirings can be defined analogously.
Definition 2.7. A category $\mathfrak{C}$ is said to be (finitely) complete iff every functor $F:\mathfrak{D}\longrightarrow\mathfrak{C},$ with $\mathfrak{D}$ a small (finite) category, has a limit. Dually, $\mathfrak{C}$ is said to be (finitely) cocomplete iff every functor $F:\mathfrak{D}\longrightarrow\mathfrak{C}$ with $\mathfrak{D}$ a small (finite) category has a colimit.
Definition 3.1. We say that a right $S$-semimodule $F$ is flat iff $F=\lim\limits_{\longrightarrow}F_{i},$ a directed limit (filtered colimit) of finitely presented projective right $S$-semimodules.
Definition 1.1. A semiring is an algebraic structure $(S,+,\cdot,0,1)$ consisting of a non-empty set $S$ with two binary operations “$+$” (addition) and “$\cdot$” (multiplication) satisfying the following conditions: 1. $(S,+,0)$ is an Abelian monoid with neutral element $0_{S};$ 2. $(S,\cdot,1)$ is a monoid with neutral element $1;$ 3. $x\cdot(y+z)=x\cdot y+x\cdot z$ and $(y+z)\cdot x=y\cdot x+z\cdot x$ for all $x,y,z\in S;$ 4. $0\cdot s=0=s\cdot 0$ for every $s\in S$ (i.e. $0$ is absorbing).
Definition 3.9. Let $M$ be a left $S$-semimodule. We say that a right $S$-semimodule $F_{S}$ is $M$-mono-flat [Kat2004a] (or $M$-$k$-flat [Alt2004]) iff $F\otimes_{S}L\leq_{S}F\otimes_{S}M$ for every $S$-subsemimodule $L\leq_{S}M.$ If $F_{S}$ is $M$-mono-flat for every left $S$-semimodule $M,$ then we call $F_{S}$ mono-flat (or $k$-flat).
Definition 2.23. We call a left $S$-semimodule $X:$ uniformly finitely generated iff there exists a uniform surjective $S$-linear map $S^{n}\longrightarrow X\overset{g}{\longrightarrow}0$ for some $n\in\mathbb{N};$ uniformly finitely presented iff ${}_{S}X$ is uniformly finitely generated and for any exact sequence of $S$-semimodules $0\longrightarrow K\overset{f}{\longrightarrow}S^{n}\overset{g}{\longrightarrow% }X\longrightarrow 0,$ the $S$-semimodule $K$ is finitely generated.
Definition 5.1. An object $T\in\mathcal{C}_{n,p}$ is called a cluster tilting object if for any object $X\in\mathcal{C}_{n,p}$ we have that $\mathrm{Ext}_{\mathcal{C}_{n,p}}^{1}(T,X)=0$ if and only if $X\in\mathrm{add}(T)$, and $\mathrm{Ext}_{\mathcal{C}_{n,p}}^{1}(X,T)=0$ if and only if $X\in\mathrm{add}(T)$.
Definition 3.3. Let $\Gamma_{n,p}$ be the quiver whose vertices are the diagonals $(i,j,k)$ of $\Pi^{p}$, and whose arrow are defined as follows. 1.: For $1\leq i<j<N$: ${\xymatrix@-8mm{&&(i,j+1,k)\\ \ar[rru]\ar[rrd](i,j,k)\\ &&(i+1,j,k)}}$ That is, we draw an arrow if there is an irreducible clockwise rotation around the vertex $j$ or $i$ inside $\Pi_{k}$, 2.: For $1\leq i<j=N$ we link $(i,N,k)\rightarrow(i+1,N,k)$ whenever there is an irreducible clockwise rotation around the vertex $N$ inside $\Pi_{k}$ 3.: For $1\leq i<j=N$ we link $(i,N,k)\rightarrow(1,i,k+1)$. That is, we draw an arrow to the diagonal we can reach with a clockwise rotation around vertex $i$ inside $\Pi_{k}$ composed with $\rho$. I.e. $(i,N,k)$ is linked to $\rho(1,i,k)=(1,i,k+1)$. The set of the operations $1.$ and $2.$ are denoted by $\mathrm{IrrRot}$ and the operations $3.$ by $\mathrm{Irr}\rho\mathrm{Rot}$.
Definition 6.5. The translation $\tau_{m}$ maps • $(i,j,k)$ to $(i-m,j-m,k)$ if $i,j\neq 1$. • If $i=1$, $\tau_{m}(1,j,k)=\rho^{-1}(1-m,j-m,k)=(1-m,j-m,k-1).$
Definition 6.8. An $m$-angulation of $\Pi^{p}$ consists of a maximal set of pairwise non crossing $m$-diagonals in $\Pi^{p}$. We denote such a set by $\mathcal{X}^{m}$.
Definition 3.6. The mesh category of a translation quiver $(Q,\tau)$ is the factor category of the path category of $Q$ modulo the ideal generated by the mesh relations $r_{v}:=\sum_{\alpha:u\rightarrow v}\alpha\cdot\sigma(\alpha),$ where the sum is over all arrows ending in $v$, and $v$ runs through the vertices of $Q$.
Definition 6.2. The $m$-diagonals of $\Pi^{p}$ are given by the union of the $m$-diagonals in each region $\Pi_{k}$, for $1\leq k\leq p$.
Definition 3.1. We call diagonals of $\Pi^{p}$ the union of all diagonals of $\Pi_{1}\cup\Pi_{2}\cup\dots\cup\Pi_{p}.$
Definition 2.4. One says that a category $\mathcal{K}$ with Serre functor $\nu$ is a fractionally Calabi-Yau category of dimension $\frac{m}{n}$ or $\frac{m}{n}$-Calabi-Yau if there is an isomorphism of triangle functors: $\nu^{n}\cong[m],$ for $n,m>0$, and where $[m]$ indicates the composition of the shift functor with itself $m$ times.
Definition 3.4. The translation $\tau$ on $\Gamma_{n,p}$ maps • $(i,j,k)$ to $(i-1,j-1,k)$ for $1<i,j\leq N$ and $1\leq k\leq p$, i.e. $\tau$ is an anticlockwise rotation around the center of $\Pi^{p}$ by $\frac{2\pi}{p(n+2)}$. • $(1,j,k)$ to $(j-1,N,k-1)$, i.e. the effect of $\tau$ on $(1,j,k)$ is induced by $\frac{1}{N}$th anticlockwise rotation in the regular $N$-gon $\Pi$ homotopic to $\Pi_{k}$, composed with $\rho^{-1}$. That is $(1,j,k)\mapsto(j-1,N,k)\mapsto(j-1,N,k-1)=\rho^{-1}(j-1,N,k).$
Definition 6.7. An object $T\in\mathcal{\mathcal{missing}}{C}^{m}_{n,p}$ is called $m$-rigid if it is the direct sum of non isomorphic indecomposable objects $T_{1},\dots,T_{t}$ such that $\mathrm{Ext}^{i}_{\mathcal{C}^{m}_{n,p}}(T_{j},T_{k})=0$ for all $1\leq i\leq m,$ and $1\leq j,k\leq t$. It is called maximal $m$-rigid if it is $m$-rigid and maximal with respect to this property. An $m$-cluster tilting object is an object $T$ in $\mathcal{C}^{m}_{n,p}$ which is $m$-rigid and such that $X\in\mathrm{add}T$ if and only if $\mathrm{Ext}^{i}_{\mathcal{C}^{m}_{n,p}}(T,X)=0$ for $1\leq i\leq m$, and $X\in\mathrm{add}T$ if and only if $\mathrm{Ext}^{i}_{\mathcal{C}^{m}_{n,p}}(X,T)=0$ for $1\leq i\leq m$.
Definition 2.2. A $k$-triangulated category $\mathcal{K}$ has a Serre functor if it is equipped with an auto-equivalence $\nu:\mathcal{K}\rightarrow\mathcal{K}$ together with bifunctorial isomorphisms $D\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{K}}(X,Y)\cong\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{K}}(Y,\nu X),$ for each $X,Y\in\mathcal{K}$. $D$ indicates the vector space duality $\mathrm{Hom}_{k}(?,k)$.
Definition 6.4. Let $\Gamma^{m}_{n,p}$ be the quiver of $m$-diagonals of $\Pi^{p}$. Its vertices are the $m$-diagonals, and the arrows are given as follows. 1.: If $j\neq N-(m-1)$, ${\xymatrix@-8mm{&&(i,j+m,k)\\ \ar[rru]\ar[rrd](i,j,k)\\ &&(i-m,j,k)}}$ 2.: If $j=N-(m-1)$ then $(i,N-(m-1),k)\rightarrow(i-m,N-(m-1),k)$. 3.: Furthermore, $(i,N-(m-1),k)\rightarrow(1,i,k+1)$.
Definition 2.6. The repetitive cluster category $\mathcal{C}_{n,p}:=\mathcal{D}/<\tau^{-p}[p]>$ of type $A_{n}$, has as class of objects the same as in $\mathcal{D}$. The class of morphism is given by: $\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}_{n,p}}(X,Y)=\bigoplus_{i\in\mathbb{Z}}\mathrm{Hom}_{% \mathcal{D}}(X,(\tau^{-p}[p])^{i}Y)$
Definition 2.3. A triangle functor between two triangulated categories $\mathcal{J}$ and $\mathcal{K}$ is a pair $(F,\sigma)$ where $F:\mathcal{J}\rightarrow\mathcal{K}$ is a $k$-linear functor and $\sigma:F[1]\rightarrow[1]F$ an isomorphism of functors such that the image of a triangle in $\mathcal{J}$ under $F$ is a triangle in $\mathcal{K}$. Suppose $(F,\sigma)$ and $(G,\gamma)$ are triangle functors, then a morphism of triangle functors is a morphism of functors $\alpha:F\rightarrow G$ such that the square $\xymatrix{F[1]\ar[d]^{\alpha[1]}\ar[r]^{\sigma}&[1]F\ar[d]^{[1]\alpha}\\ G[1]\ar[r]^{\gamma}&[1]G}$ commutes.
Definition 1.1.1. A collection of objects ${\mathcal{I}}$ in a tensor category ${\mathcal{T}}$ is called an ideal of ${\mathcal{T}}$ if the following conditions are satisfied: (i) $X\otimes Y\in{\mathcal{I}}$ whenever $X\in{\mathcal{T}}$ and $Y\in{\mathcal{I}}$. (ii) If $X\in{\mathcal{T}}$, $Y\in{\mathcal{I}}$ and there exist $\alpha:X\to Y$, $\beta:Y\to X$ such that $\beta\circ\alpha=\text{id}_{X}$, then $X\in{\mathcal{I}}$.
Definition 4. A $\mathsf{2}$-algebra $(C,c_{0},c_{1})$ is homotopy-initial if for any $\mathsf{2}$-algebra $(D,d_{0},d_{1})$, the type $\mathsf{2}\text{-}\mathsf{Alg}\big{[}(C,c_{0},c_{1}),(D,d_{0},d_{1})\big{]}$ is contractible.
Definition 1. A type $A$ is called contractible if the type $\mathsf{iscontr}(A)=_{\mathrm{def}}(\Sigma x:A)(\Pi y:A)\mathsf{Id}_{A}(x,y)$ is inhabited.
Definition 7. A $P$-algebra $(C,s_{C})$ is homotopy-initial if for every $P$-algebra $(D,s_{D})$, the type $P\text{-}\mathsf{Alg}\big{[}(C,s_{C}),(D,s_{D})\big{]}$ of weak algebra maps is contractible.
Definition 3. Let $f:A\rightarrow B$. • We say that $f$ is a weak equivalence if the type $\mathsf{isweq(f)}=_{\mathrm{def}}(\Pi y:B)\,\mathsf{iscontr}(\mathsf{hfiber}(f% ,y))$ is inhabited. • We say that $f$ is a homotopy equivalence if there exist a function $g:B\rightarrow A$ and elements $\displaystyle\eta$ $\displaystyle:(\Pi x:A)\mathsf{Id}(gfx,x)\,,$ $\displaystyle\varepsilon$ $\displaystyle:(\Pi y:B)\mathsf{Id}(fgy,y)\,.$ It is an adjoint homotopy equivalence if there are also terms $\displaystyle p$ $\displaystyle:(\Pi x:A)\mathsf{Id}(\varepsilon_{fx}\,,f\,\eta_{x})\,,$ $\displaystyle q$ $\displaystyle:(\Pi y:B)\mathsf{Id}(\eta_{gy}\,,g\,\varepsilon_{y})\,,$ where the same notation for both function application and the action of a function on an identity proof (which is easily definable by $\mathsf{Id}$-elimination), and we write $\alpha_{x}$ instead of $\alpha(x)$ for better readability.
5.11 Definition A chiral CFT ${\cal A}$ is a quadruple $(H_{0},A(\cdot),U,\Omega)$, where $H_{0}$ is a separable Hilbert space (thus essentially independent of ${\cal A}$), $\Omega\in H$ a unit vector, $U$ is a strongly continuous positive-energy representation of the group $PSU(1,1)$ on $H$, and for each $I\in{\cal I}$, $A(I)\subset B(H_{0})$ is a von Neumann algebra. These data must satisfy the following axioms: (i) ‘Isotony’: $I_{1}\subset I_{2}\Rightarrow A(I_{1})\subset A(I_{2})$ (i) ‘Locality’: $I_{1}\cap I_{2}=\emptyset\Rightarrow[A(I_{1}),A(I_{2})]=\{0\}$. (iii) ‘Irreducibility’: $\cap_{I}A(I)^{\prime}={\mathbb{C}}{\bf 1}$. (iv) ‘Möbius Covariance’: If $I\in{\cal I},g\in{\cal P}$ then $U(g)A(I)U(g)^{*}=A(gI)$. (v) $U(g)\Omega=\Omega\ \forall g\in{\cal P}$.
8.1 Definition Two non-degenerate braided fusion categories ${\cal C}_{1},{\cal C}_{2}$ are called Witt equivalent if there are fusion categories ${\cal D}_{1},{\cal D}_{2}$ such that there is a braided equivalence ${\cal C}_{1}\boxtimes Z_{1}({\cal D}_{1})\simeq{\cal C}_{2}\boxtimes Z_{1}({% \cal D}_{2})$.
3.3 Definition A pivotal category [37, 38] is a tensor category together with a left duality ${}^{\vee}\!-$ and a monoidal natural isomorphism $\gamma:\mathrm{id}\rightarrow{}^{\vee\vee}\!-$.
5.20 Definition A modular category ${\cal C}$ is called prime if every modular fusion subcategory is either trivial or equivalent to ${\cal C}$.
4.9 Definition Let ${\cal C}$ be a braided tensor category. An algebra $(A,m,\eta)$ in ${\cal C}$ is called commutative if $m\circ c_{A,A}=m$. A commutative separable algebra is called étale.
3.2 Definition A left duality on a tensor category is an assignment $X\mapsto({}^{\vee}\!X,e_{X},d_{X})$, where ${}^{\vee}\!X$ is a left dual of $X$, the morphisms $e_{X}:{}^{\vee}\!X\otimes X\rightarrow{\bf 1},\ d_{X}:{\bf 1}\rightarrow X% \otimes{}^{\vee}\!X$ satisfying the above identities. Similarly, a right duality is an assignment $X\mapsto(X^{\vee},e^{\prime}_{X},d^{\prime}_{X})$ where the morphisms $e^{\prime}_{X}:X\otimes X^{\vee}\rightarrow{\bf 1},\ d^{\prime}_{X}:{\bf 1}% \rightarrow X^{\vee}\otimes X$ establish $X^{\vee}$ as a right dual of $X$.
5.13 Definition A chiral CFT ${\cal A}=(H,A(\cdot),U,\Omega)$ is called completely rational if the following holds: (i) ‘Split property’: If $I_{1},I_{2}\in{\cal I}$ satisfy $\overline{I_{1}}\cap\overline{I_{2}}=\emptyset$ then the natural map $A(I_{1})\otimes_{alg}A(I_{2})\rightarrow A(I_{1})\vee A(I_{1})$ induces an isomorphism of von Neumann algebras. (ii) ‘Strong additivity’: If $I_{1},I_{2}\in{\cal I}$ satisfy $\#(\overline{I_{1}}\cap\overline{I_{2}})=1$ (i.e. the intervals are disjoint but adjacent) then $A(I_{1})\vee A(I_{2})=A(I)$, where $I$ is the interior of the closure of $I_{1}\cup I_{2}$. (iii) ‘Finiteness’: Let $I_{1},I_{2}\in{\cal I}$ such that $\overline{I_{1}}\cap\overline{I_{2}}=\emptyset$. Then $(I_{1}\cup I_{2})^{\prime}=I_{3}\cup I_{4}$ for certain $I_{3},I_{4}\in{\cal I}$. The quantity $\mu(A)=[(A(I_{3})\vee A(I_{4})^{\prime})^{\prime}:A(I_{1})\vee A(I_{2})]$ (which a priori is in $[1,\infty]$ and can be shown to be independent of $I_{1},I_{2}$) is finite.
4.3 Definition Let ${\cal C}$ be a BTC. (a) Two objects $X,Y\in{\cal C}$ are said to commute if $c_{X,Y}=\widetilde{c}_{X,Y}$, equivalently $c_{X,Y}\circ c_{Y,X}=\mathrm{id}_{Y\otimes X}$. (b) Let ${\cal D}\subset{\cal C}$ be a subcategory. The centralizer $C_{\cal C}({\cal D})$ is the full subcategory of ${\cal C}$ defined by $\mathrm{Obj}\,C_{\cal C}({\cal D})=\{X\in{\cal C}\ |\ c_{X,Y}\circ c_{Y,X}=% \mathrm{id}_{Y\otimes X}\ \forall Y\in{\cal D}\}.$ (c) The symmetric center $Z_{2}({\cal C})$ is defined as $C_{\cal C}({\cal C})$, i.e. the full subcategory defined by $\mathrm{Obj}\,Z_{2}({\cal C})=\{X\in{\cal C}\ |\ c_{X,Y}\circ c_{Y,X}=\mathrm{% id}_{Y\otimes X}\ \forall Y\in{\cal C}\}.$
6.4 Definition [24] A braided fusion category ${\cal C}$ is called almost non-degenerate if $Z_{2}({\cal C})\simeq$SVect. (Equivalently, $Z_{2}({\cal C})$ has precisely one non-trivial simple object $X$ satisfying $X^{2}\cong{\bf 1}$ and $\theta_{X}=-\mathrm{id}$.)
3.18 Definition If ${\cal M}$ is a category, $\mathrm{End}\,{\cal M}$ denotes the category whose objects are the endofunctors of ${\cal M}$, i.e. functors ${\cal M}\rightarrow{\cal M}$, and whose morphisms are the natural transformations of these endofunctors. With $\otimes$ defined as composition of functors, $\mathrm{End}\,{\cal M}$ is a strict tensor category. An alternative name for $\mathrm{End}\,{\cal M}$ is $Z_{0}({\cal M})$, the monoidal center of ${\cal M}$.
5.1 Definition A braided fusion category ${\cal C}$ is called • pre-modular if it is spherical, • non-degenerate if $Z_{2}({\cal C})$ is trivial, • modular if it is pre-modular and non-degenerate. Such a ${\cal C}$ is called just ‘modular category’ or MTC.
3.10 Definition If ${\cal C}$ is a tensor category and $(A,m,\eta)$ is an algebra in ${\cal C}$ then a left $A$-module (in ${\cal C}$) is a pair $(X,\mu)$ where $X\in{\cal C}$ and $\mu:A\otimes X\rightarrow X$ satisfies $\mu\circ(m\otimes\mathrm{id}_{X})=\mu\circ(\mathrm{id}_{A}\otimes\mu)$ and $\mu\circ(\eta\otimes\mathrm{id}_{X})=\mathrm{id}_{X}$. $\@tabarray{l}\kilglu\kern 22.5pt\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){\kern-3.749943pt${X}$}\hss% }\\\kilglu\kern 7.5pt\kilglu\hbox{\put(1.0,0.0){\oval(2.0,2.0)[lt]}\put(1.0,0.% 0){\line(0,1){2.0}}}\kilglu\kern 4.5pt\raise 3.0pt\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){$\mu$}}% \\\kilglu\kern-10.5pt\raise 3.0pt\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){$m$}}\kilglu\kern 10.5pt% \kilglu\hbox{\put(0.5,0.0){\oval(1.0,1.0)[ct]}\put(0.5,0.5){\line(0,1){0.5}}}% \kilglu\kern 7.5pt\kilglu\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){\line(0,1){1.0}}}\\\hbox{\put(0.0% ,0.0){\kern-3.749943pt${A}$}\hss}\kilglu\kern 15.0pt\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){\kern-% 3.749943pt${A}$}\hss}\kilglu\kern 7.5pt\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){\kern-3.749943pt${X% }$}\hss}\@close@row\quad=\quad\@tabarray{l}\kilglu\kern 30.0pt\hbox{\put(0.0,0% .0){\kern-3.749943pt${X}$}\hss}\\\kilglu\hbox{\put(2.0,0.0){\oval(4.0,2.0)[lt]% }\put(2.0,0.0){\line(0,1){2.0}}}\kilglu\kern 4.5pt\raise 3.0pt\hbox{\put(0.0,0% .0){$\mu$}}\\\kilglu\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){\line(0,1){2.0}}}\kilglu\kern 15.0pt% \kilglu\hbox{\put(1.0,0.0){\oval(2.0,2.0)[lt]}\put(1.0,0.0){\line(0,1){2.0}}}% \kilglu\kern 4.5pt\raise 3.0pt\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){$\mu$}}\\\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0)% {\kern-3.749943pt${A}$}\hss}\kilglu\kern 15.0pt\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){\kern-3.749% 943pt${A}$}\hss}\kilglu\kern 15.0pt\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){\kern-3.749943pt${X}$}% \hss}\@close@row\quad\quad\quad\quad\quad\quad\@tabarray{l}\kilglu\kern 15.0pt% \hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){\kern-3.749943pt${X}$}\hss}\\\kilglu\hbox{\put(1.0,0.0){% \oval(2.0,2.0)[lt]}\put(1.0,0.0){\line(0,1){2.0}}}\kilglu\kern 4.5pt\raise 3.0% pt\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){$\mu$}}\\\raise 3.0pt\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){$\eta$}}\kilglu% \hbox{\put(0.0,1.0){\line(0,1){1.0}}\put(0.0,0.8){\circle{0.4}}}\kilglu\kern 1% 5.0pt\kilglu\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){\line(0,1){2.0}}}\\\kilglu\kern 15.0pt\hbox{% \put(0.0,0.0){\kern-3.749943pt${X}$}\hss}\@close@row\quad\quad=\quad\quad% \@tabarray{l}\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){\kern-3.749943pt${X}$}\hss}\\\kilglu\hbox{% \put(0.0,0.0){\line(0,1){2.0}}}\\\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){\kern-3.749943pt${X}$}% \hss}\@close@row$ The left $A$-modules in ${\cal C}$ form a category, denoted $A$-$\mathrm{Mod}_{\cal C}$ or ${}_{A}{\cal C}$, with hom-sets $\mathrm{Hom}_{{}_{A}{\cal C}}((X,\mu),(X^{\prime},\mu^{\prime}))=\{t\in\mathrm% {Hom}_{\cal C}(X,X^{\prime})\ |\ t\circ\mu=\mu^{\prime}\circ(\mathrm{id}_{A}% \otimes t)\}.$ Right modules and bimodules are defined analogously.
5.12 Definition Let ${\cal A}=(H,A(\cdot),U,\Omega)$ be a chiral CFT. A representation of ${\cal A}$ is a pair $(H,\{\pi_{I}\}_{I\in{\cal I}})$, where $H$ is a (separable) Hilbert space and $\{\pi_{I}:A(I)\rightarrow B(H)\}_{I\in{\cal I}}$ is a family of $*$-representations satisfying $\pi_{I_{2}}\upharpoonright A(I_{1})=\pi_{I_{1}}$ whenever $I_{1}\subset I_{2}$. A morphism of representations $(H,\{\pi_{I}\}),(H^{\prime},\{\pi^{\prime}_{I}\})$ is a bounded operator $V:H\rightarrow H^{\prime}$ such that $V\pi_{I}(\cdot)=\pi^{\prime}_{I}(\cdot)V$ for each $I\in{\cal I}$. This defines a $*$-category $\mathrm{Rep}\,{\cal A}$. If $(H,\{\pi_{I}\})$ is a representation, we define $\dim\pi=[\pi_{I^{\prime}}(A(I^{\prime})^{\prime}):\pi_{I}(A(I))]\in[1,\infty]$, where the brackets denote the Jones index, and the r.h.s. is independent of $I\in{\cal I}$. $\mathrm{Rep}_{f}{\cal A}$ denotes the full subcategory of $\mathrm{Rep}\,{\cal A}$ of representations with $\dim\pi<\infty$.
4.1 Definition Let ${\cal C}$ be a braided tensor category with braiding $c$. The opposite braiding $\widetilde{c}$ is defined by $\widetilde{c}_{X,Y}=(c_{Y,X})^{-1}$. The tensor category ${\cal C}$ equipped with the braiding $\widetilde{c}$ is denoted $\widetilde{{\cal C}}$. In the graphical calculus (where we draw morphisms going upwards) the braidings $c$ and $\widetilde{c}$ are represented by $c_{X,Y}=\@tabarray{l}\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){\kern-3.749943pt${Y}$}\hss}\kilglu% \kern 30.0pt\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){\kern-3.749943pt${X}$}\hss}\\\kilglu\hbox{\put% (0.0,2.0){\line(1,-1){0.7}}\put(0.0,0.0){\line(1,1){2.0}}\put(2.0,0.0){\line(-% 1,1){0.7}}}\\\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){\kern-3.749943pt${X}$}\hss}\kilglu\kern 30.0% pt\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){\kern-3.749943pt${Y}$}\hss}\@close@row\quad\quad\quad% \quad\widetilde{c}_{X,Y}=\@tabarray{l}\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){\kern-3.749943pt${Y}% $}\hss}\kilglu\kern 30.0pt\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){\kern-3.749943pt${X}$}\hss}\\% \kilglu\hbox{\put(0.0,2.0){\line(1,-1){2.0}}\put(0.0,0.0){\line(1,1){0.7}}\put% (2.0,2.0){\line(-1,-1){0.7}}}\\\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){\kern-3.749943pt${X}$}\hss}% \kilglu\kern 30.0pt\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){\kern-3.749943pt${Y}$}\hss}\@close@row$ which is consistent in view of the isotopy $c_{Y,X}\circ\widetilde{c}_{X,Y}=\quad\@tabarray{l}\kilglu\hbox{\put(0.0,2.0){% \line(1,-1){0.7}}\put(0.0,0.0){\line(1,1){2.0}}\put(2.0,0.0){\line(-1,1){0.7}}% }\\\kilglu\hbox{\put(0.0,2.0){\line(1,-1){2.0}}\put(0.0,0.0){\line(1,1){0.7}}% \put(2.0,2.0){\line(-1,-1){0.7}}}\@close@row\quad=\quad\@tabarray{l}\kilglu% \hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){\line(0,1){2.0}}}\kilglu\kern 15.0pt\kilglu\hbox{\put(0.0,% 0.0){\line(0,1){2.0}}}\@close@row\quad=\mathrm{id}_{X\otimes Y}.$
8.4 Definition Let ${\cal C}_{1},{\cal C}_{2}$ be modular categories. A modular invariant for $({\cal C}_{1},{\cal C}_{2})$ is a triple $(A_{1},A_{2},E)$, where $A_{1}\in{\cal C}_{1},A_{2}\in{\cal C}_{2}$ are connected étale algebras and $E:{}_{A_{1}}{\cal C}_{1}^{0}\rightarrow{}_{A_{2}}{\cal C}_{2}^{0}$ is a braided equivalence.
3.11 Definition An algebra $(A,m,\eta)$ in a tensor category is called separable if the multiplication morphism admits a splitting that is a morphism of $A$-$A$ bimodules, i.e. a morphism $\widetilde{m}:A\rightarrow A\otimes A$ satisfying $(m\otimes\mathrm{id}_{A})\circ(\mathrm{id}_{A}\otimes\widetilde{m})=\widetilde% {m}\circ m=(\mathrm{id}_{A}\otimes m)\circ(\widetilde{m}\otimes\mathrm{id}_{A}% ),\quad\quad\quad m\circ\widetilde{m}=\mathrm{id}_{A}.$ $\@tabarray{l}\kilglu\hbox{\put(0.5,0.0){\oval(1.0,1.0)[ct]}\put(0.5,0.5){\line% (0,1){0.5}}}\kilglu\kern 15.0pt\kilglu\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){\line(0,1){1.0}}}\\% \kilglu\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0){\line(0,1){1.0}}}\kilglu\kern 15.0pt\kilglu\hbox{% \put(0.5,1.0){\oval(1.0,1.0)[cb]}\put(0.5,0.0){\line(0,1){0.5}}}\@close@row% \quad=\quad\@tabarray{l}\kilglu\hbox{\put(0.5,1.0){\oval(1.0,1.0)[cb]}\put(0.5% ,0.0){\line(0,1){0.5}}}\\\kilglu\hbox{\put(0.5,0.0){\oval(1.0,1.0)[ct]}\put(0.% 5,0.5){\line(0,1){0.5}}}\@close@row\quad=\quad\@tabarray{l}\kilglu\hbox{\put(0% .0,0.0){\line(0,1){1.0}}}\kilglu\kern 15.0pt\kilglu\hbox{\put(0.5,0.0){\oval(1% .0,1.0)[ct]}\put(0.5,0.5){\line(0,1){0.5}}}\\\kilglu\hbox{\put(0.5,1.0){\oval(% 1.0,1.0)[cb]}\put(0.5,0.0){\line(0,1){0.5}}}\kilglu\kern 15.0pt\kilglu\hbox{% \put(0.0,0.0){\line(0,1){1.0}}}\@close@row\quad\quad\quad\quad\quad\quad\quad% \@tabarray{l}\kilglu\hbox{\put(0.5,0.0){\oval(1.0,1.0)[ct]}\put(0.5,0.5){\line% (0,1){0.5}}}\\\kilglu\hbox{\put(0.5,1.0){\oval(1.0,1.0)[cb]}\put(0.5,0.0){% \line(0,1){0.5}}}\@close@row\quad=\quad\@tabarray{l}\kilglu\hbox{\put(0.0,0.0)% {\line(0,1){2.0}}}\@close@row$ If ${\cal C}$ is $k$-linear and $\dim\mathrm{Hom}({\bf 1},A)=1$ then the algebra $(A,m,\eta)$ is called connected.
6.1 Definition [18] A modularization of a pre-modular category ${\cal C}$ is a functor $F:{\cal C}\rightarrow{\cal D}$ of braided fusion categories, where ${\cal D}$ is modular and $F$ is surjective (or ‘dominant’) in the sense that every object of ${\cal D}$ is a subobject of one of the form $F(X)$ with $X\in{\cal C}$.
4.12 Definition Let ${\cal C}$ be a (strict) tensor category with braiding $c$ and left duality $X\mapsto({}^{\vee}X,e_{X},d_{X})$. A ribbon structure on ${\cal C}$ is a natural isomorphism $\Theta:\mathrm{id}_{\cal C}\rightarrow\mathrm{id}_{\cal C}$, i.e. a natural family of isomorphisms $\Theta_{X}:X\rightarrow X$, satisfying $\displaystyle\Theta_{X\otimes Y}$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle(\Theta_{X}\otimes\Theta_{Y})\circ c_{Y,X}\circ c_{X,Y}\quad% \forall X,Y$ $\displaystyle\Theta_{{}^{\vee}\!X}$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle{}^{\vee}(\Theta_{X})\quad\forall X.$
3.1 Definition Let ${\cal C}$ be a tensor category and let $X,Y\in{\cal C}$. If there exist morphisms $e:Y\otimes X\rightarrow{\bf 1},\ d:{\bf 1}\rightarrow X\otimes Y$ satisfying $(\mathrm{id}_{X}\otimes e)\circ(d\otimes\mathrm{id}_{X})=\mathrm{id}_{X},\quad% \quad\quad(e\otimes\mathrm{id}_{Y})\circ(\mathrm{id}_{Y}\otimes d)=\mathrm{id}% _{Y},$ then $Y$ is called a left dual of $X$ and $X$ is a right dual of $Y$. If every object has a left (right) dual, we say that ${\cal C}$ has left (right) duals.
5.16 Definition Let $V$ be a finite dimensional complex vector space and $\pi:SL(2,{\mathbb{Z}})\rightarrow\mathrm{End}(V)$ a representation. A vector valued modular form of type $\pi$ is a holomorphic map $\rho:{\mathbb{H}}\rightarrow V$ satisfying $f(g^{-1}z)=\pi(g)f(z)\quad\forall z\in{\mathbb{H}},\ g\in SL(2,{\mathbb{Z}}).$ Here ${\mathbb{H}}=\{z\in{\mathbb{C}}\ |\ \mathrm{Im}\,z>0\}$ and $SL(2,{\mathbb{Z}})$ acts on ${\mathbb{H}}$ by $\left(\begin{array}[]{cc}a&b\\ c&d\end{array}\right)z=\frac{az+b}{cz+d}$.
4.7 Definition Let ${\cal C}$ be a BTC, ${\cal D}$ a tensor category and $F:{\cal C}\rightarrow{\cal D}$ a tensor functor. A central structure on $F$ is a braided tensor functor $\widehat{F}:{\cal C}\rightarrow Z_{1}({\cal D})$ such that $K\circ\widehat{F}=F$. Here $K:Z_{1}({\cal D})\rightarrow{\cal D}$ is the tensor functor that forgets the half-braiding, thus $\widehat{F}$ is a lift of $F$ from ${\cal C}$ to $Z_{1}({\cal C})$.
3.8 Definition Let ${\cal C}$ be a strict tensor category. An algebra (or monoid) in ${\cal C}$ is a triple $(A,m,\eta)$, where $A\in{\cal C}$, $m:A\otimes A\rightarrow A$ and $\eta:{\bf 1}\rightarrow A$ satisfy $m\circ(m\otimes\mathrm{id}_{A})=m\circ(\mathrm{id}_{A}\otimes m)$ (associativity) and $m\circ(\eta\otimes\mathrm{id}_{A})=\mathrm{id}_{A}=m\circ(\mathrm{id}_{A}% \otimes\eta)$ (unit property). If ${\cal C}$ is non-strict, one inserts associativity isomorphisms at the appropriate places.
